Head.
Slightly to more obviously shorter than broad, ratio of length to breadth across eyes 10.0:11.4–15.3; slightly raised medially on anterior half, slightly depressed above antennal insertions; punctures fine on raised area of head, becoming larger towards sides and posterior, at sides separated by less than diameter, none confluent; eyes generally large, moderately flat, dorsally separated across head by 8.9–13.3× breadth of eye in dorsal view; temple very small; antenna short, with gradually developed 4-segmented club (
Fig. 99
), apical segment small; ventral side of head with deep convergent antennal grooves as in the other two known species (
Fig. 101
).

Male genitalia.
(
Fig. 96–97
) With median strut and internal sac similar to 

E. elongatus

(see 
Fig. 108–109
) but with 25–26 chitinous rods on each side; median lobe of moderate length, shallowly emarginate and with 4–5 short setae on each side; parameres long with long setae along apical two thirds of both margins, a few shorter ones nearer base (
Fig. 97
); sternites 8 and 9 appearing moderately elongate, sternite 8 produced at sides (
Fig. 96
)
